         <div>
            <head>2.7.1884 Mittwoch</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49069">Hamburg</placeName> July 2. 1884
      Wednesday.</p>
            <p>Very hot in the morning came away at 12 o&#x2019;clock from school. but
      at about half past four it began not to pour but to come down in buckets. This
      is no exaggeration. The wind kept on turning so that the water came in at every
      open window, and with the rain it hailed and lightened and thundered so
      fearfully that at times we were really afraid the windows would smash. It had
      hardly rained ten minutes when we heard a kind of rushing noise under the
      pantry floor and suddenly the water began to squirt out of a hole in the floor
      like a fountain; nothing could stop it. The water came higher and higher, it
      flooded the kitchen, the servants room, the pantry in fact the whole ground
      floor, till it went over our boots. And horrible dirty water it was too. And
      this did not happen in our house alone but in every other house on the
      <placeName key="59484">Uhlenhorst</placeName> too because they did not open the
      drain soon enough.</p>
